[Dr Yosef's contribution is very welcome, in view
of the need for enhanced involvement of
ornithologists in the global effort to control
H5N1 and prevent its marching -- or rather
flying? -- invasive spread. The growing concern
about the possible role that migratory birds
might play in the dissemination of the virus is
underlined by the season: a combination of
southwards bird migration, targeting the
Near-East on the way to Africa -- where control
measures might encounter serious difficulties --
on the one hand; and the seasonal, winter's
upsurge of influenza (including avian influenza) incidence on the other hand.

A comprehensive review paper titled "Potential
risk of HPAI spreading through wild water bird
migration", including maps, has been prepared by
FAO's avian influenza task force (Rome and
Bangkok) and published in issue No 33 of
FAO-AIDE-NEWS update on the avian influenza
situation, as of 1 Sep 2005. See
<http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/subjects/documents/ai/AVIbull033.pdf>.

Readers are referred to the listed previous postings, and especially to:
1. Posting 20050625.1786 with comments from the Wildlife Conservation Society;
2. Posting 20051031.3181 with a call for wild-bird identification.
3. Posting 20051102.3196, commentary -- table,
listing the reported cases of HPAI in wild birds in 2004/2005.- Mod.AS]
